Name: Centripetal Force Equation
Short_Desc: Centripetal force of object moving in circular path.

Name: Centripetal Acceleration
Short_Desc: Find centripetal acceleration of object along circular path at constant velocity

Name: Kinetic Energy
Short_Desc: Find kinetic energy of point mass by velocity

Name: Velocity Equation
Short_Desc: Equation to find final velocity of object undergoing acceleration

Name: Ohms Law
Short_Desc: Ohm's law states that the current through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the voltage across the two points.

Name: Electrical Power - Voltage, Current
Short_Desc: Ohms law to solve for electrical power from voltage and current.

Name: Rotational Kinetic Energy
Short_Desc: Rotational energy or angular kinetic energy is kinetic energy due to the rotation of an object and is part of its total kinetic energy. Looking at rotational energy separately around an object's axis of rotation, the following dependence on the object's moment of inertia is observed.

Name: Bernoullis Principle
Short_Desc: In fluid dynamics, Bernoulli's principle states that an increase in the speed of a fluid occurs simultaneously with a decrease in static pressure or a decrease in the fluid's potential energy.

Name: Circumference of Circle
Short_Desc: Find circumference of a circle.

Name: Pendulum Equation of motion
Short_Desc: Simple pendulum time to complete full period based off gravity and length.

Name: Density
Short_Desc: The density of a substance is its mass per unit volume.

Name: Drag Force
Short_Desc: In fluid dynamics, drag is a force acting opposite to the relative motion of any object moving with respect to a surrounding fluid. This can exist between two fluid layers or a fluid and a solid surface.

Name: Buoyancy Force
Short_Desc: Buoyancy or up thrust, is an upward force exerted by a fluid that opposes the weight of a partially or fully immersed object.

Name: Area of a circle
Short_Desc: In geometry, the area enclosed by a circle of radius r is πr2. Here the Greek letter π represents the constant ratio of the circumference of any circle to its diameter, approximately equal to 3.1416.

Name: Electrical Conductance
Short_Desc: Electrical conductance measures the ease with which an electric current passes.

Name: Potential Energy
Short_Desc: Potential energy of an object due to it's mass, gravity, and distance relative to ground.

Name: EOM 1
Short_Desc: Equation of motion to solve for final velocity under constant acceleration.

Name: Normal Stress
Short_Desc: Stress experienced throughout a bar in tension or compression along it's axis.

Name: Ideal Gas Law
Short_Desc: The ideal gas law is used to determine the state of a hypothetical ideal gas.

Name: Newtons Universal Gravitation
Short_Desc: Newton's law of universal gravitation is usually stated as that every particle attracts every other particle in the universe with a force that is directly proportional to the product of their masses and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between their centers.

Name: Area of a trapezoid
Short_Desc: In English outside North America, a convex quadrilateral in Euclidean geometry, with at least one pair of parallel sides, is referred to as a trapezium; in American and Canadian English this is usually referred to as a trapezoid

Name: Linear Momentum
Short_Desc: In Newtonian mechanics, linear momentum, translational momentum, or simply momentum is the product of the mass and velocity of an object.

Name: Equation of Motion distance
Short_Desc: Equation of motion to solve for distance under constant acceleration

Name: Capacitance
Short_Desc: Capacitance is the ratio of the amount of electric charge stored on a conductor to a difference in electric potential.

Name: Newtons Second Law
Short_Desc: Newton's second law describes a simple relationship between the acceleration of an object with mass m, and the net force Fnet acting on that object

Name: Rotational Power
Short_Desc: In rotational systems, power is the product of the torque τ and angular velocity ω.

Name: Friction Force
Short_Desc: The Coulomb friction {\displaystyle F_{\mathrm {f} }\,}F_{\mathrm {f} }\, may take any value from zero up to {\displaystyle \mu F_{\mathrm {n} }\,}\mu F_{\mathrm {n} }\,, and the direction of the frictional force against a surface is opposite to the motion that surface would experience in the absence of friction.

Name: Lift Force
Short_Desc: A fluid flowing around an object exerts a force on it. Lift is the component of this force that is perpendicular to the oncoming flow direction.

Name: Electric Power
Short_Desc: Electric power is the rate, per unit time, at which electrical energy is transferred by an electric circuit.

Name: Angular Acceleration
Short_Desc: In physics, angular acceleration refers to the time rate of change of angular velocity.

Name: Angular Velocity
Short_Desc: A measure of how fast an object rotates around another point.

Name: Angular Momentum
Short_Desc: In physics, angular momentum (rarely, moment of momentum or rotational momentum) is the rotational analog of linear momentum.

Name: Quadratic Formula
Short_Desc: In elementary algebra, the quadratic formula is a formula that provides the solution(s) to a quadratic equation.

Name: Volumetric Flowrate
Short_Desc: In physics and engineering, in particular fluid dynamics, the volumetric flow rate (also known as volume flow rate, rate of fluid flow, or volume velocity) is the volume of fluid which passes per unit time

Name: Specific Heat Capacity
Short_Desc: Used to find the thermal energy of a process.

Name: Thermal Resistance
Short_Desc: Thermal resistance is a heat property and a measurement of a temperature difference by which an object or material resists a heat flow. Thermal resistance is the reciprocal of thermal conductance.

Name: Combined Gas Law
Short_Desc: Combining the laws of Charles, Boyle and Gay-Lussac gives the combined gas law, which takes the same functional form as the ideal gas law save that the number of moles is unspecified, and the ratio of PV to T is simply taken as a constant:

Name: Cuolumbs Law
Short_Desc: Coulomb's inverse-square law, or simply Coulomb's law, is an experimental law of physics that quantifies the amount of force between two stationary, electrically charged particles. The electric force between charged bodies at rest is conventionally called electrostatic force or Coulomb force.

Name: Equivalent Resistance
Short_Desc: Equivalent resistance of two resistors in parallel.

Name: Torque
Short_Desc: Torque is referred to as the rotational equivalent of force.

Name: Mass flow equation
Short_Desc: In physics and engineering, mass flow rate is the mass of a substance which passes per unit of time.

Name: Pressure Volume Work
Short_Desc: Work done by a system undergoing a constant pressure volume change.

Name: Entropy Production
Short_Desc: Entropy Production

Name: Pythagorean theorem
Short_Desc: The Pythagorean theorem is a fundamental relation in Euclidean geometry among the three sides of a right triangle.

Name: Heat transfer coefficient
Short_Desc: It is used in calculating the heat transfer, typically by convection or phase transition between a fluid and a solid.

Name: Future value
Short_Desc: Future value is the value of an asset at a specific date. It measures the nominal future sum of money that a given sum of money is worth at a specified time in the future assuming a certain interest rate. It is the present value multiplied by the accumulation function.

Name: Hagen-Poiseuille
Eqn: ΔP = 8 * π * μ * L * Q / A ^ 2
Short_Desc: In nonideal fluid dynamics, the Hagen–Poiseuille equation, also known as the Hagen–Poiseuille law, Poiseuille law or Poiseuille equation, is a physical law that gives the pressure drop in an incompressible and Newtonian fluid in laminar flow flowing through a long cylindrical pipe of constant cross section

Name: Beam Bending End Loaded Cantilever
Short_Desc: Elastic deflection from a point load at end of a cantilevered beam.

Name: Inductance Formula
Short_Desc: Inductance is a property of an electrical conductor that causes it to resist changes in the electric current passing through it. The flow of electric current generates a magnetic field around a conductor.

Name: Parallel Resistances
Short_Desc: Total resistance for N number of resistances in parallel
